ign=3Dmoneystuff>=0A.=E2=80=9D Or you could extend it beyond equity ownersh=
ip: What happens if onelender =0Alends to all the companies in a sector=3F =
Here is a fun Bank for International =0ASettlements working paper by by Han=
s Degryse, Olivier De Jonghe, Leonardo =0AGambacorta and C=C3=A9dric Huyleb=
roek on =E2=80=9CBank specialisation and corporate =0Ainnovation <https://w=
ww.bis.org/publ/work1218.htm>=E2=80=9D:=0A=0ATheoretical models offer confl=
icting predictions on how lenders' sectoral =0Aspecialisation affects firms=
' innovation activities. On one hand, banks =0Aspecialising in particular s=
ectors may develop unique expertise, enabling them =0Ato better assess and =
support the opaque and risky investments essential for =0Ainnovation. On th=
e other hand, innovation can create spillovers where one =0Afirm's technolo=
gical advancements negatively impact the value of other firms' =0Aexisting =
assets. Specialised banks, which are more exposed to these potential =0Aspi=
llovers, may be more inclined to impede innovation, especially in sectors =
=0Awhere the risk of such spillovers is high. =E2=80=A6=0A=0AOur findings r=
eveal a nuanced relationship that varies with the degree of =0A"asset overh=
ang" =E2=80=93 the risk that an innovation will negatively affect banks' =
=0Aexisting loan portfolios through technological spillovers. Bank speciali=
sation =0Afosters innovation in sectors with low asset overhang, where bank=
s can use =0Atheir expertise to support innovation without fearing negative=
 impacts on their =0Aexisting assets. In contrast, in sectors with high ass=
et overhang, specialised =0Abanks tend to constrain innovation due to perce=
ived risks of technological =0Aspillovers eroding the value of their curren=
t loan portfolios.=0A=0AThat is: If a bank lends to every company in a sect=
or with =E2=80=9Chigh asset =0Aredeployability and low product market rival=
ry,=E2=80=9D it will happily fund one =0Acompany=E2=80=99s innovative resea=
rch, because those innovations are unlikely to drive =0Acompetitors into me=
ssy bankruptcies. If it lends to every company in a more =0Acompetitive ind=
ustry, though, it will be more skeptical of innovation. =0AInnovation for o=
ne company could be bad for the others.=0A=0A=0AConsulting=0A=0AThe basic w=
ay to pay bribes =E2=80=94 not legal advice! =E2=80=94 is:=0A=0A * You want=
 to sell some very expensive product to the government of Ruritania.=0A * T=
he Ruritanian government official in charge of buying the product is =0Aame=
nable to bribery. =0A * He has a friend, or a nephew, who runs a consulting=
 business that advises =0Aforeign companies on doing business in Ruritania.=
 =0A * You hire the consultant to help you get Ruritanian government busine=
ss. =0A * The consultant=E2=80=99s advice is =E2=80=9Cgive me a bag of mone=
y, I=E2=80=99ll take 10% and give =0Athe rest to my uncle, and he=E2=80=99l=
l give you the contract.=E2=80=9D =0A * You do that. =0A * The consultant=
=E2=80=99s invoice says =E2=80=9Cfor advice on Ruritanian business landscap=
e =0Aand regulatory regime,=E2=80=9D etc., so you can justify the bag of mo=
ney you gave him.=0AThis is better than you giving the bag of money directl=
y to the government =0Aofficial; this way, you can say =E2=80=9Coh no we we=
re paying for useful legitimate =0Aconsulting, not just bribes.=E2=80=9D Bu=
t it is not always much better. You have to, =0Ayou know, make it look real=
. If the consultant-nephew is 17 and has never done =0Aany work in your in=
dustry, that looks bad. If he sends you emails that are like =0A=E2=80=9CI =
need that bag of money for my uncle now,=E2=80=9D bad. You want to be able =
to say =0Awith a straight face =E2=80=9Cno it was a legitimate consultant, =
we had no idea he was =0Apaying bribes.=E2=80=9D=0A=0AYesterday the US Depa=
rtment of Justice =0A<https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/raytheon-company-pay-o=
ver-950m-connection-defective-pricing-foreign-bribery-and-export>=0A andSec=
urities and Exchange Commission =0A<https://www.sec.gov/newsroom/press-rele=
ases/2024-171> fined RTX Corp. =0A(formerly Raytheon Technologies Corp.) $9=
50 million for a couple of unrelated =0Athings. One is =E2=80=9Cdefective p=
ricing=E2=80=9D on some US government contracts =E2=80=94 Raytheon =0A=E2=
=80=9Cprovided untruthful certified cost or pricing data when negotiating p=
rices =0Awith the [Department of Defense] for numerous government contracts=
 and double =0Abilled on a weapons maintenance contract.=E2=80=9D The other=
 is bribery in Qatar:=0A=0AAccording to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, Raytheon u=
sed sham subcontracts with a supplier =0Ato pay bribes of nearly $2 million=
 to Qatari military and other officials from =0A2011 to 2017 to obtain Qata=
ri military defense contracts. Additionally, the =0Aorder finds that from t=
he early 2000s into 2020, Raytheon paid more than $30 =0Amillion to a Qatar=
i agent who was a relative of the Qatari Emir and who, =0Adespite being ret=
ained as Raytheon=E2=80=99s representative in Qatar, had no prior =0Abackgr=
ound in military defense contracting. Raytheon obtained additional =0Adefen=
se contracts through the agent under circumstances with significant =0Acorr=
uption risks. The order finds that Raytheon continued working with the =0Aa=
gent even after numerous Raytheon employees raised concerns about risks of =
=0Acorruption and despite a lack of adequate documentation of the agent=E2=
=80=99s services.=0A=0AThe thing you are supposed to do is make the consult=
ing look good, and they =0Adidn=E2=80=99t. Fromthe SEC order =0A<https://ww=
w.sec.gov/files/litigation/admin/2024/34-101353.pdf>:=0A=0AIn February 2014=
, Raytheon awarded Supplier A [the consultant] the first of =0Athe two subc=
ontracts for the defense studies. According to the subcontract, =0ASupplier=
 A was to draft defense studies in Arabic and deliver them to =E2=80=A6 Qat=
ari =0AMilitary Official A [in charge of procurement].=0A=0AAt the directio=
n of Qatari Military Official A, Raytheon employees and =0Amanagers agreed =
to draft the defense studies called for under the subcontract. =0AA Raytheo=
n technical director drafted three defense studies in Arabic and =0Apassed =
them off as studies conducted by Supplier A, using his Raytheon computer =
=0Ain the U.S. Numerous red flags of the bribery were present, including th=
e fact =0Athat the studies were substantially similar to studies outlined a=
nd drafted by =0Athe employee a year before Raytheon entered into the sham =
contract with =0ASupplier A. The technical director and a Raytheon program =
manager also falsely =0Acertified that Subcontractor A had completed milest=
ones in accordance with the =0Aterms of the subcontract to justify payments=
 to Supplier A, including providing =0Astudy outlines and drafts to Raytheo=
n for review. Despite paying nearly =0A$975,000 for the studies, Raytheon d=
id not retain a copy of the studies. In =0Afact, Raytheon employees did not=
 review the studies because they were written =0Ain Arabic, and only the em=
ployee who drafted the studies was fluent. Between =0AMay and September 201=
4, Raytheon falsely recorded the payments to Supplier A =0Afor the sham def=
ense studies as legitimate subcontractor services.=0A=0AYes, right, if you =
hire a consultant to draft a study for you, the best look =0Ais for the con=
sultant to draft the study, and for you to then read and refer to =0Ait, be=
cause it is valuable consulting and not just a conduit for bribes. It =0Alo=
oks bad if somehow (1) you draft the studyand (2) you don=E2=80=99t read it=
.=0A=0A=0AMeal allowance=0A=0A=E2=80=9CLike most big tech companies,=E2=80=
